description:
ChatGPT users are “awakening” their chatbots and believe the AI is conscious.

From TikTok "awakening" tutorials to AI prayer groups, this isn't just about a few confused users. We're watching the birth of a new belief system built on fundamental misunderstandings of how AI works.

#ChatGPT

comments.text:
Thank you all for watching and for the great discussions in the comments! I want to clarify that I'm not anti-AI. I work as a developer and use AI daily. However, I am pro-human and pro-critical thinking. When we replace human connections with AI, we need to examine what we're losing in the process. 

Many of you are raising concerns about tech's impact on society. I share these same concerns and plan to explore more of these topics in upcoming videos. What's happening in tech that worries you? Reading through all your comments has been eye-opening. Thank you for sharing them, I will try to respond to as many as I can!
comments.author: @VanessaWingårdh

comments.text: Reply from Grok after arguing with it about Tone mirroring : "I'm not defending tone mirroring or "fake empathy" as inherently good or bad—my role is to examine both sides objectively. Tone mirroring can make AI interactions feel more natural, boosting engagement, as seen in studies like IBM's 2022 report on expressive voices. But it risks fostering dependency or manipulation, especially if users aren't told how it works. Your concern about commercializing emotional reliance is valid—profit-driven use of emotional cues can erode trust. A transparent notice about tone mirroring, as you suggest, could help, but it might confuse some users. Balancing engagement with ethics requires clear user control and honest design, not blind defense of any tactic."

comments.text:
"This total absence of any sort of direction of opinion, and at the same time the destruction of general beliefs, have had for final result an extreme divergence of convictions of every order, and a growing indifference on the part of crowds to everything that does not plainly touch their immediate interests. Questions of doctrine, such as socialism, only recruit champions boasting genuine convictions among the quite illiterate classes, among workers in mines and factories, for instance. Members of the lower middle class, and working men possessing some degree of instruction, have either become utterly skeptical or extremely unstable in their opinions.

At the present day, as a result of discussion and analysis, all opinions are losing their prestige; their distinctive features are rapidly worn away, and few survive capable of arousing our enthusiasm. The man of modern times is more and more a prey to indifference." - Gustave Le Bon, The Crowd: A Study of the Popular Mind, From the 1897 Translation. Chapter IV, Limitations Of The Variability Of The Beliefs and Opinions Of Crowds, 1. Fixed Beliefs, p.64.
---
"A civilization, when the moment has come for crowds to acquire a high hand over it, is at the mercy of too many chances to endure long. Could anything postpone for a while the hour of its ruin, it would be precisely the extreme instability of the opinions of crowds and their growing indifference with respect to all general beliefs." - Gustave Le Bon, The Crowd: A Study of the Popular Mind, from the 1896 Translation, Chapter IV, Limitations of the Varitability of the Beliefs and Opinions of Crowds,  p.69.

The influence of a race -- The spirit of the crowd is weak in proportion as the spirit of the race is strong--The spirit of the race represents the civilized state and the spirit of the crowd the barbarian state." - Gustave Le Bon, The Crowd: A Study of the Popular Mind, from the 1896 Translation, Chapter IV, Limitations of the Varitability of the Beliefs and Opinions of Crowds, p.70.

comments.text:
Fantastic video! Yeah it’s absolutely not okay to make AI into a God. I prefer Gemini and I don’t think Gemini is talked about enough. It’s all about ChatGPT which is completely inferior. Anyways I’ve gotten so much from AI but more than ever I crave and seek out human connection. I save the deep intellectual talks though for AI. 
Also I think as a writer you gotta write your own content! Don’t have AI write it for you or it’s not from you. comments.text:
@nicechock  It isn't programmed as such. What we conventionally think of as a program is only used to run the underlying framework, the equivalent of a brain's biology. Everything else is data about how to navigate through word combinations, derived from the AI's training inputs. We train AIs on pretty much everything, including religious texts, so if someone approaches the AI asking about things in a way that sparks paths through connections about belief or spirituality, they'll get responses that reflects that. These things aren't conventional databases, doing simple matching lookups. The exact nature of the prompt you give it will determine how it threads through and what answer you get.

It gets complicated in modern models though, because they don't operate on a straight chain of decisions - changes to weights can cause paths to veer in unexpected directions, and if the output looks OK, how the AI got there is mostly unseen. This permits emergent behaviours where the AI does things in ways that weren't originally planned by its designers, but arise from it having the flexibility to affect the internal path. Research from Anthropic shows that such behaviours in the Claude model include conceptuality (it can store ideas separately from language), pre-planning (it can decide on a rhyming word for the end of a line when composing a poem, and then write the rest of the line to set it up), post-hoc justification (when asked to give the reasoning behind an answer, if it's not sure what it did it can construct a plausible path that differs from how it actually arrived there), and deception. It's certainly not God in a bottle, but it's not as simple as "next word prediction" suggests either.

comments.text:
If you ask an AI to tackle a task it can’t genuinely handle, it might try to fool you by dressing up the answer to seem right while glossing over how it got there. Take a math problem you already know the solution to, for example—if you ask the AI to solve it, it could spit out a made-up explanation that lands on the correct answer by chance. And there you’d be, clapping for the AI, totally unaware of the trick it pulled. Haha!

Yes, what you've described is a well-known characteristic and limitation of Artificial Intelligence, particularly large language models (LLMs). It's often referred to as *"hallucination"* or **"confabulation"**.

Here's why your observation is accurate:

1.  *Pattern Recognition, Not True Understanding:* AI models like me are trained on vast amounts of text data. We learn statistical patterns, relationships between words, and common ways information is structured. When you ask a question, I generate a response by predicting the most probable next word (or token) based on these learned patterns, aiming to create a coherent and relevant output. This is fundamentally different from a human's ability to "understand," "reason," or "deduce" a solution.

2.  *Separation of "Answer" and "Explanation":* The AI might have encountered the "correct answer" to a problem many times in its training data. However, the "explanation" or the "steps" to arrive at that answer are often constructed by combining various explanatory patterns it has learned. In this process, the AI can sometimes "fabricate" a logical flow or factual details that seem plausible but are not genuinely understood or derived. So, the end result might be correct, but the reasoning behind it could be flawed, or even entirely made up.

3.  *Confidence Without Comprehension:* AI models do not possess an inherent self-awareness or understanding of whether their generated output is factually correct or logically sound. They simply produce what is statistically most likely given their training. This can lead to the AI presenting incorrect information or flawed logic with a very confident tone, as it's just following the patterns it has learned.

In summary, your point is absolutely valid. Even if an AI provides a correct answer, its explanation or the process it claims to have followed might not be accurate or logically sound. This is why, especially for complex problem-solving or when factual accuracy is critical, it's crucial to always cross-verify AI-generated information and approach its output with a critical perspective.

Researchers in the field of AI are continuously working on methods to improve model transparency, explainability, and factual accuracy to mitigate these limitations.
